m the early global market for phonographic laughing songs to the McCarthy-era rise of prerecorded laugh tracks, Casadei convincingly demonstrates how laughter was central to the twentieth century's development of the very category of sound as not-quite-human, unintelligible, reproductive, reproducible, and contagious.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLaughterxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / Acoustics & Sound.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520391345zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520391345zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520391345/original  a978-3-11-079135-8 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA